DAT
id=qid::label=str::title=lstr::detail=lstr::
1::library_001::Archer [Servant]::    Heroic Spirits of the bow. Archer Servants tend to have low base abilities, but are armed with powerful Skills and Noble Phantasms. The Archer in this story follows this trend and fights his battles using several unknown Noble Phantasms.	    Archer is a sarcastic realist...but he also has an oddly childish side that makes him hard to hate. His true identity is â– â– â– â– â– â–  â– â– â– â– â– . He plays an important background role and could be considered a hidden main character through half of Fate. His alleged memory loss due to his botched summoning at the beginning of the game was a half-truth. That night, he understood his situation after Rin went to sleep, deduced the current circumstances, and became convinced that his long-awaited opportunity had finally come.	    He became sure that Rin Tohsaka (whose name he truly had forgotten) summoned him once the girl introduced herself. At that moment, Archer's memories came flooding back at lightning speed.		    "Then, 'Rin.' Yes, the sound of that..."		    Unbeknownst to Rin, he uttered that with maddening affection.	    Much around Archer serves to foreshadow future events, but the moment that skirted closest to outright prophecy was his parting remark in the Fate route, before fighting Berserker.	    The feedback from using magecraft changed his skin color... That's what we went with, anyway.::
2::library_002::Einzbern forest	 [Miscellaneous]::    An expansive, mountainous forest on the outskirts of Fuyuki City. It is more like uncharted wilderness than just undeveloped land. It takes about one hour to travel there by car from town.	    A giant Bounded Field is deployed within the interior. Anyone who enters is easily detected by Illya unless they mask their presence and magical energy.	    Illya's castle headquarters is located in the center of the forest.::
3::library_003::Aozaki [Person]::    The name Aozaki is mentioned in passing during this story, and it refers to the mage family who administers the highest-quality spiritual land in Japan. It is an infamous name within mage society. The Aozaki are an old but not especially prestigious lineage. Some generations ago, the Aozaki patriarch opened a path to the Root, and subsequent family heads have had a high probability of becoming Magicians.	    The current Aozaki successors are a notorious pair of sisters. After an inheritance struggle, the younger sister won the title of Magician. The older sister went to London and became a renowned mage, but apparently left the Clock Tower due to differences of opinion. During the events of the Fifth Holy Grail War in Fuyuki, it is believed that the older sister is in hiding, while the younger sister is on an easygoing tour of Japan.	    The younger sister's only talent is destruction, while the older sister has a master artist's temperament. They may or may not have a very slight level of involvement in the events of <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic>.::
4::library_004::Red cloak 	[Armament]::    Variously mentioned as Archer's cloak, coat, or mantle, this red garment is iconic of Archer, and is in truth a Conceptual Weapon of the highest caliber. It protects not against foes, but the external world itself, and is said to be made from the shroud of a saint.::
5::library_005::Assassin [Servant]::    Heroic Spirits who specialize in assassination. Unlike the other classes, only a select group of Heroic Spirits can take on this class.	    Unusually, a samurai Assassin protects the mountain gate to Ryudou Temple. Sasaki Kojirou was summoned in this class because his summoner violated the rules of the Holy Grail War. To be precise, he is a wraith rather than a Heroic Spirit. He is believed to be a martial artist connected to Ryudou Temple. His True Name is unknown; rather, he has no name.	    Perhaps because there was never any possibility of improving his station in life, Assassin has no sense of greed. His sole wish was to live by the sword, culminating in his otherworldly mastery which stands on par with a Servant's Noble Phantasm. In terms of pure swordsmanship, he is the greatest Servant of this Holy Grail War.	    Because Assassin was summoned using Ryudou Temple's mountain gate as the catalyst, he cannot leave the gate.	    ...Wait, so the gate's haunted?::
6::library_006::Unlimited 	Blade Works 	[Miscellaneous]::    The title of Rin's route, and the subtitle of <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> when the story was still in its drafting stages.	    We actually distributed booklets at Winter Comic Market in 2001. How many people in Japan even noticed it was there and realized that it teased a future title!?::
7::library_007::Rarity 	[Miscellaneous]::    Standing portraits that show up only once during the main story.	    <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> prides itself on having a pretty insane amount of standing portraits, and some art was drawn only for specific scenes. Depending on the choices you make, you might never encounter them in your life.	   Some of the more notable pieces are Saber getting out of the bath, bashful Rin, hugging Rin, and comically angry Saber.	   There are actually more that never made it into the final product, because the game already required a lot of time to play through, and because it boasts silly features such as the Tiger Dojos.::
8::library_008::Illyasviel von 	Einzbern [Person]::    A quasi-heroine, and the Master of Berserker.	    In this story, Illya the mysterious loli girl who makes contact with Shirou when he's still completely clueless and calls him "Big Brother." She has demeanor that's both innocent and cruel, and is interested in Shirou for some reason. We hope she gives you the impression that angel and demons are two sides of the same coin.	    She is the most powerful Master ever to exist thanks to the Command Spells engraved all over her entire body, her extraordinary quantity of Magic Circuits compared to typical mages, and so forth. One could say that she was born to win the Holy Grail War.	    Illya becomes a key character in each route, but her identity and true nature only come to light in the final route. Prior to that, she's just the friendly, adorable little troublemaker who shows up to murder Shirou.	    She might have had her own route during the story draft stage... Alas, it would have delayed <fzitalic>Fate's</fzitalic> release by half a year, so it was not to be.::
9::library_009::Illya's maids 	[Miscellaneous]::    The maids who accompany Illya.	    Our key animator kept making a fussâ€”I mean, got involved in their design, so it was decided that they'd appear in the game.	    Sella is the governess, while Leysritt is Illya's confidant. Don't tell anyone, but Liz might have the biggest boobs in Fate.	    The maids were originally defective Holy Grail homunculi who were slated for disposal, but received a slight extension on life through their assignment to Illya. 	    As an aside, Illya's caretaker was originally planned to be an unpleasant German man in a suit, who would harass and irritate Shirou and Rin at every turn.::
10::library_010::Incantation 	[Magecraft]::    One of the actions taken during the activation of magecraft.	    There are various recognized incantation lengths, such as Single Actions activated by the simple flow of magical energy, single-verse spells that fix a phenomenon within the caster's body, ten-count Instant Contracts taking at least ten verses to enact simple rituals, and so forth.	    Rin's Gandr Shot and Rider's Mystic Eyes are classified as Single Actions. Shirou and Archer's incantations are mostly five verses or longer, approaching ten-count incantations.	    Caster's incantation is one verse long, but her spells activate instantly, as fast or faster than Single Actions. Her spells are at least as poweful as five-count magecraft, and this is why she is beyond the ability of most mages to handle.	    Incidentally, Caster's incantations are Divine Words that are not limited by the constraints of Single Actions and verses. This is why they can overcome Magic Resistance of rank B or C.::
11::library_011::Heroic Spirit::    What heroes become when they achieve great feats during their lifetimes and become subjects of worship after death.	    Heroic Spirits are the highest powers that exist to protect humanity. They are classified as similar to Elementals rather than ghosts or wraiths. Whereas Elementals manifest as power molded according to human imagination, humanity's ideals are woven into the very essence of Heroic Spirits. Heroic Spirits consist of the legendary, the real, and the unobserved. Those who lack worship are largely classified as Guardians and are used as part of the mindless Counter Force.	    Among the Heroic Spirits who appear in this story, Archer is the only one who functions as a Guardian. The others are either too divine or aligned too closely with the planet to count as Guardians.::
12::library_012::Kiritsugu Emiya 	[Person]::    A freelance mage. He died at the age of 34.	    For better or worse, as Shirou's foster father, Kiritsugu set the direction of Shirou's life. He was also Saber's Master in the previous Holy Grail War, and survived to win the war.	    Kiritsugu favored firearms and was proficient in a unique magecraft called Innate Time Control. His aptitude as a Master was average, but he specialized at killing mages. In a word, he was the Association's hitman, and it is believed the Einzberns hired him for that skill set.	    During the Holy Grail War, Kiritsugu reportedly acted so villainously that it made Kotomine look like a green whelp. He took an enemy Master's lover hostage and even demolished a high-rise building just to target one person. Though, Kotomine was in fact quite young at the time.	    Kiritsugu even had a wife and a mistress. Perhaps such is the fate of all capable men.	    When he wasn't acting as a mage, he was a radical feminist, lecturing Shirou not to make girls cry, lest he regret it later.	    ...Wait, what's feminist about that?	    At the end of the Fourth Holy Grail War, Kiritsugu was tainted by the very same AĹ‹ra Mainiiu whom Kotomine welcomed. This resulted in his death several years later.::
13::library_013::Shirou Emiya [Person]::  It needn't be said that Shirou is the protagonist of this story.	  He is a hardworking young man whose interests include cooking, cleaning, and needlework. He denies this, claiming that there's no one else at home to do them, but it's obviously not true. He's the house-husband all stay-at-home dads should aspire to be.	  Putting his inherent butler-like disposition to good use, after the True Ending of Rin's route, he ends up working part time at the household of Rin's rival. What's up with that?	  Although he remains a rather poor mage until the end of his days, he manages to become a very successful user of magecraft.::
14::library_014::The king's speech	[Miscellaneous]::    The way Gilgamesh talks. You write his first-person pronoun as "ware" but pronounce it "ore."	    Nothing could be more arrogant, but then again, Shirou isn't exactly being humble if he can criticize Gil to his face after being dragged into this whole Holy Grail business.	    As an aside, Gil gets mad if you talk to him. He'll react like, "How dare this rabble speak to me!?"::
15::library_015::Gate of Babylon 	[Noble Phantasm]::    The Treasury of the King is a key-shaped sword that connects to the golden city and allows the user to freely draw out the contents of the treasury.	    It goes without saying that this Noble Phantasm is more powerful the wealthier its user is.	    As for why its name is literally "Gate of Babylon" in English, it's because Babylon also has a reputation as an evil city or a golden city.	    There might also be imitations named Lord of Babylon or so forth.::
16::library_016::Protection Against 	the Wind [Magecraft]::    True Assassin used this ability to evade Invisible Air.	    For some reason, it was displayed in the game with a black-colored font.	    It was originally supposed to be named "â—‹â—‹â—‹ is â—‹â—‹â—‹â—‹â—‹," but we scrapped that for grown-up reasons.::
17::library_017::Kanshou and Bakuya 	[Noble Phantasm]::    A.K.A. Gan Jiang and Mo Ye. Archer favors these married yin-yang swords.	    During the Spring and Autumn era of Chinese history, the king of Wu commissioned the swordsmith Gan Jiang to forge a sword fit for a king. However, work on the sword did not go well, and Gan Jiang was at his wit's end. His wife Mo Ye could not bear to see her husband in anguish, and staked her life on his work. After all, crafting a sword worthy of the gods requires a human sacrifice. Mo Ye threw herself into her beloved husband's furnace before his very eyes, giving her life to create an alloy of Five-Mountains Essence and Six-Heroes Iron. In his grief, Gan Jiang created two swords, naming them Gan Jiang and Mo Yeâ€”a pair of married swords symbolizing yin and yang.	    Forged from the finest materials and a human life, these are capable swords, but they are also useful as magical and ritual weapons. A ward against evil is engraved on them, perhaps reflecting Archer's personal tastes.::
18::library_018::Gandr [Magecraft]::    A curse passed down through northern Europe. The caster points a finger at the target of the curse, ruining their health. It is also known as the Gandr Shot, due to the need to focus it on a single target.	    Gandr may be the origin of why it's considered rude to point at another person.	    The Finn Shot, a stronger version of the Gandr Shot, deals damage directly to its target. Rin's Gandr is violent and on the same level as the Finn Shot. It's basically a Finn Gatling.::
19::library_019::Bellerophon 	[Noble Phantasm]::  Bellerophon, the Bridle of Chivalry, is an unusual Noble Phantasm that consists of a set of reins and a whip which, of course, have no effects when used individually.	  Bellerophon has a Noble Phantasm rank of A+ and boasts exceptional offensive and defensive abilities. When this Noble Phantasm is invoked, the winged horse under its control has its limiters removed. All of its ability scores are boosted by one rank, and it is protected by a massive amount of magical energy that increases its defensive power by several times.	  While Saber's Excalibur manifests as a golden flare, Rider's empowered steed could be described as a white comet.	  Bellerophon is the man in Greek mythology who mastered riding Pegasus. He is also known as Bellerophontes or Hipponous.::
20::library_020::Kischur Zelretch 	Schweinorg [Person]::    A.K.A. the Wizard Marshal or Kaleidoscope, Zelretch of the Jewels is one of the five current Magicians. (He is also one of the vampiric Dead Apostle Ancestors, but this was omitted from the story as it is irrelevant to <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic>.)	    Zelretch is a mage symbolized by jewels. He's a strange old man who treats evil with righteous indignation and good with laughter, and a monster who once fought a duel against the king of the vampires a really long time ago and stopped an asteroid from falling onto the Earth with brute force. Since then, however, he's aged considerably, and it appears that he can no longer wield the Magic of his prime.	    He is known to take apprentices on a whim, but a lineage that would succeed him has yet to emerge. Incidentally, becoming his apprentice is almost guaranteed to result in being rendered useless for the rest of one's life.	    During the episode described in Sakura's True Ending, the department Lords of the Mage's Association faced a dilemma: Only their most promising candidates would have any chance of coming back in one piece, but they would suffer a heavy loss if Zelretch ended up causing irreparable damage to their best talent.::
21::library_021::Caster [Servant]::    The mage Heroic Spirit which specializes in magical energy, and is said to be the weakest Servant.	    Her Master is Souichirou Kuzuki. Her identity is Medea from Greek mythology, who is infamous for being a treacherous witch. She has a losing role in Saber's route, while she gets to flaunt her villainy in Rin's route.	    Medea was once pure of heart, but became tainted by evil after numerous betrayals. "Fine, if that's how you want to be, then I'll take you all down with me!" How earnest!	    Of course, she always had a wicked streak, but at the end of the day, Miss Caster is a maiden in love.	    I'm pretty sure if Shirou went and told on her, "Mr. Kuzuki, Caster's being naughty," she would make adorable puppy eyes at him. Yeah.	    Beneath her robes, she's one of the most beautiful women in this story. She would give her heart and soul for her beloved, but due to the trauma of all her lovers fleeing her, she's always thinking one step ahead.	    Argh, too bad; I bet a Caster route would have been a lot of fun, damn it! There could be a trap where you'd cheat on her with Rider and then she'd stab you in the back.	ă€€As an aside, Caster's abilities as a mage are Magician-level, but Caster never learned any Magic herself, so she's just a mage.::
22::library_022::Strengthening 	[Magecraft]::    An elementary type of magecraft that is extremely difficult to master.	    Stregthening involves the channeling of magical energy to elevate the target's existence. While it is a fundamental of all magecraft, its high degree of freedom and lack of executable forms means that there are few well-rounded Strengthening users.	    Shirou is, of course, an inexperienced user who can only perform it on weapons.	    Strengthening specializes the target's very raison d'etre; a knife becomes sharper, food becomes more nutritious, and a maid becomes more moe.	    Something that is too vague cannot be Strengthened to be even more vague. Also, other people are the hardest of all to Strengthen because it's difficult to pass one's own magical energy into living things.::
23::library_023::Gilgamesh [Servant]::  Humanity's oldest King of Heroes, and the Archer of the previous Holy Grail War who defeated Saber. See his in-game Status screen for details.	  Gilgamesh can be considered a Servant-killer. No proper Heroic Spirit can beat him. Among the Servants in this story, he is undoubtedly the strongest.	  He has lost battles for various reasons. He lost once as a result of his obsession in a battle against Saber, while it was due to his arrogance when fighting Shirou, and it was because of his carelessness during his bout against [redacted]. But he's a Servant who is without equal when he's fighting seriously.	  He's become rather fashionable, perhaps thanks to living in human society for the last ten years. He has a bunch of different outfits, and the biker suit he wears in Rin's route is one of his favorites. So much so, in fact, that he let Shirou and company escape just because he didn't want to get it dirty. What a shockâ€”the protagonist's life is worth less than Gil's clothes...!	  You might wonder how he managed to last this long without causing any trouble, but Gil might be more self-conscious than he's given credit for. Apparently, he drank a certain Noble Phantasm to change his appearance and personality.	  When we were designing Gil, I selfishly asked for him to be in full golden plate armor. You could say it's because I'm from the generation that challenged that 60-floor tower over and over!::
24::library_024::Goldy 	[Miscellaneous]::    What Rin called Gilgamesh after seeing him. He isn't golden because of what he looks like when he's fully armed, but because it's the color of his soul.	    Gil has the most money in this story. His compatibility with the money-grubbing Rin is...			    <fzfscale=2>THE VERY BEST.</fzfscale>		    But that's our little secret, okay?::
25::library_025::Argon Coin 	[Noble Phantasm]::    The Argon Coin, or the Golden Fleece, was an extremely valuable treasure of the ancient land of Colchis.	    ...It has no particular powers of its own, but for some reason, legends stated that a dragon would appear if said sheepskin was thrown on the ground.	    Some say that the dragon that once guarded the Golden Fleece became the fleece itself. It sounds like satire.	    Caster can't summon the dragon because she doesn't have the skill to summon dragons.	    An odd spirit dwells within it. Say hi to that Seventh Holy Scripture for us.::
26::library_026::Souichirou Kuzuki 	[Person]::    A teacher at the high school that Shirou and his friends go to. He teaches Modern Society and Ethics.	    Kuzuki is Caster's Master, but is a normal person, not a mage.	    He's a mysterious person who arrived in Fuyuki about two years ago. The abbot of Ryudou Temple took a liking to him, and he's lived there since thanks to the abbot's kindness.	    Kuzuki calls himself a ruined killer, implying that he must have killed someone in the past. His close-combat skills are his own, rather than something Caster gave him.	    Just as Caster felt affection for Kuzuki, Kuzuki found meaning in living with Caster. As someone who was made to fight as a living corpse, he resembles the protagonist Shirou in a way.	    He seems to have been part of an organization similar to the Nanaya family in Tsukihime.	    Kuzuki's the number-one character I'd like to expand upon if given the opportunity.::
27::library_027::The Shadow [???]::    An unidentified entity that resembles a jellyfish on land. Conventional attacks don't affect it at all. Whoever encounters it can only end up dead or wait for it to disappear on its own.	    It's a surprise enemy that shows up just when you're getting tired of the jokes in Saber and Rin's routes.	    It's our animator's favorite. They love the Shadow so much they edited the illustration where it first appears into a cool wallpaper. We couldn't be more different.::
28::library_028::5-dan in kendo 	[Miscellaneous]::It's an amazing accomplishment to achieve 5-dan at Fuji-nee's age. Shirou doesn't have a chance against her in a kendo match.::
29::library_029::Darkening	[Miscellaneous]"::    The state of being contaminated and transformed by an unidentified curse.	    When a Servant is Darkened, its alignment and personality are inverted. The Servant becomes more powerful thanks to gaining a concrete, physical body as a true familiar.	    Not unlike a certain evil revived cyborg group, except pretty much a whole new character with a heavily altered design.::
30::library_030::Gotou [Person]::    Shirou's classmate. He's a cheerful, impressionable teenager whose speaking pattern changes daily based on the TV dramas he watched the night before.::
31::library_031::Kirei Kotomine 	[Person]::  An overseer dispatched from the Mage's Association and the Holy Church, the two foremost organizations of the magical world.	   Kirei is the Master of the previous Archer and secretly Lancer's Master. When Kirei was in his early twenties, he fought in the Holy Grail War that his father oversaw. Afterward, he was transfered from the Church to the Association. He then inherited the role of overseer, as a survivor of the fourth war.	   Kirei is qualified as a Church Executor and specializes in spiritual healing. While he is an exemplary Executor, he probably wouldn't stand a chance against the Burial Agency's seventh-ranked member.	   Still, he displays superior offensive power against spiritual beings, which is a testament to how unshakeable his faith is (distorted as that faith may be).	   While it may seem as though Kirei favors destruction, he is actually a mage who <fzitalic>creates</fzitalic>, like Shirou. His spiritual and psychological healing skills are on par with a prelate's.	   He's an evil man who isn't a villain. A fiend who isn't inhuman. He's the greatest enemy in <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic>.	   If Archer is an existence whose light brings Shirou's shortcomings to the forefront, one could say that Kotomine is like a wall that causes those faults to stand out in stark releif against its darkness. 	   The initial concept for Kotomine was "the guy that you instantly know is plotting something behind the scenes the moment you meet him."::
32::library_032::Copenhagen 	[Miscellaneous]::    A liquor store in Shinto. Shirou's been working there part-time for the last five years.	    The owner's daughter, who's always under a kotatsu, went to high school with Fuji-nee.	    Do felines stick together...?::
33::library_033::Servant [Magecraft]::    Heroic Spirits summoned by the Holy Grail. They are classified as familiars.	    These souls of the highest purity are summoned into seven prepared molds, termed "classes," and anchored to the world by mortal hosts, termed "Masters."	    Servants are normally beyond human control. They are forced into a cooperative relationship with their Masters by Command Spells engraved at the time of summoning, which serve as absolute conditions for their incarnation.	    Servants can shift between spirit and physical forms at will. While in spirit form, they can also pass through inanimate substances that lack magical energy.	    When Lancer ambushed Shirou at home, he passed through the roof into the living room in spirit form and materialized at the living room ceiling.	    While Servants cannot be physically affected while in spirit form, they also lose the ability to interact with the physical world. It is believed to be more advantageous to take physical form during combat.::
34::library_034::Sir Bedivere [Person]::    The knight who attended to King Arthur in his final hours. He was the last knight that remained, and the one who the king commanded to return Excalibur to the lake.	    When King Arthur's knights are mentioned, names such as Lancelot, Percival, and Galahad tend to come to mind, but they were newer knights who were originally added specifically for the quest for the Holy Grail.	    The oldest, well-renowned knights whose stories precede King Arthur's are Sir Kay, Sir Gawain, and Sir Bedivere.	    Sir Bedivere was modeled after an old, Celtic war god with a name similar to his.	    As an aside, he addressed Altria using "Sir," since he never found out she was a woman.::
35::library_035::Yukika Saegusa 	[Person]::  A female student in class 2-A. Saegusa is viewed as the mascot of her friend group, but she's the most patient and mature of the trio.	  She looks up to Rin Tohsaka in her class regardless of her being an honor student.	  She has a lot of little brothers who are much younger than her. Her family may be poor, but she is generous of spirit.	  Her soothing, gentle smile and her fluffy, bunny-like demeanor stir a protective urge in the people around her.	  Yukika actually wanted to join the Culinary Appreciation Club, but Kaede Makidera forced her to manage the track and field club.	  By the way, just as everyone expects, she's extremely unathletic.::
36::library_036::GĂˇe Bolg 	[Noble Phantasm]::    GĂˇe Bolg, the Barbed Spear that Pierces with Death, is a cursed spear that absolutely pierces its target's heart once thrust.	    It's a cheat skill that reverses causality and releases the spear after the heart has been stabbed.	    No matter what the opponent does to evade, they'll be hit because the spear has already struck home.	    To evade GĂˇe Bolg, the target either needs a Noble Phantasm that resurrects them after death, like Berserker, or high enough luck (LCK) to shrug off the spear's curse.	    In gaming terms, it's a ridiculous Noble Phantasm that receives a damage bonus equal to its target's maximum HP. If we assume Saber has 100 HP, then GĂˇe Bolg deals [spear damage] + 100 HP in damage!	    So, yeah. You'd die.	    It's also a handy weapon that only costs magical energy in the double digits to activate. There's hardly a more efficient weapon when it comes to man-on-man combat.	    Incidentally, this version of GĂˇe Bolg is Lancer's personal arrangement of it. The original GĂˇe Bolg is a thrown Noble Phantasm used against armies, not individuals.::
37::library_037::Breaker Gorgon 	[Noble Phantasm]::    Breaker Gorgon, or Self-Seal Darkness Temple, seals Mystic Eyes. Rider's blindfold prevents her overly powerful Mystic Eyes from petrifying everything in her sight.	    Shirou's lewd dream in Sakura's route occurred while he was captive in the Darkness Temple. While in that dream world, Rider fed on his blood and magical energy in the guise of salacious acts.	    Still, the blindfold served its purpose.	    "Heh. Did you think I was wearing this blindfold just for show?"::
38::library_038::God Hand 	[Noble Phantasm,	 Curse]::    God Hand, or Twelve Labors, is a boon (curse) of immortality granted by the gods. 	    The user's flesh becomes stout armor and nullifies all attacks of rank B or lower. Additionally, it grants eleven resurrections (Raise) to the user that automatically occur upon death.	    ...Still, one wonders has to wonder if Berserker's body changed color and shape thanks to God Hand.	    Anyway, it's an OP Noble Phantasm that, in fighting game terms, applies Super Armor + No Damage to all attacks other than Super Combos. That's gotta be the strongest one out there.::
39::library_039::Meal [Miscellaneous]::    Something indispensible in the Emiya household. Also, something you shouldn't give Saber any more of than necessary.	    Level up her expectations too much, and she'll give you a dissatisfied glare for any lesser meals. A fearsome beast indeed.::
40::library_040::Shirou's bedroom 	[Miscellaneous]::    The room our protagonist Shirou sleeps in, it need not be said.	    It's almost impressive how empty it is, like the room of a bachelor who just moved into a new place.	    Fuji-nee often leaves random junk in here, but Shirou always puts it away in the shed.	    Kinda reminds me of a houseboy.::
41::library_041::True Assassin 	[Servant]::    The true Assassin Heroic Spirit of the Holy Grail War. He is summoned by Zouken Matou and incarnates using Sasaki Kojirou's body.	    He's stereotypical image of cloak-and-dagger assassin, wearing a white skull mask and a black robe. His physical abilities aren't extraordinary, but he's a user-friendly Servant. He has a loyal nature beneath his unsettling appearance, and he'll never betray someone he recognizes as his master.	    To begin, the title Assassin refers to a group of wraiths (Heroic Spirit candidates), so his Servant's powers are weak. He modifies his body to better oppose other Servants.	    Assassin has no face beneath the mask. His skin and nose have been removed, making him "no one." This is how he inherited the seat of the Old Man of the Mountain.	    While Assassin initially incarnated with low intelligence, his cognitive power was dramatically boosted when he acquired Lancer's heart. Afterward, Lancer's personality continued to influence him.	    By the way, he's quite fond of the dirks he fights with, and makes sure to pick them all up after each battle.::
42::library_042::Avalon 	[Noble Phantasm]::    Avalon, Ever the Distant Utopia, is a sheath that bears the name of the eternally springtime fairyland from the legend of King Arthur. It is associated with the island utopia from which the apples of immortality came in Greek mythology.	    The Einzberns excavated Excalibur's sheath in Cornwall and gave it to Kiritsugu as a catalyst to summon King Arthur.	    The sheath not only heals wounds and stops aging; it disassembles into hundreds of parts when its True Name is invoked, protecting its bearer from all forms of interference. It is a Noble Phantasm is on the realm of True Magic, isolating the user from physical interference, travel across parallel worlds, and multi-dimensional communication (up to the sixth dimension).	ă€€There's nothing anyone can do if Saber were to shut herself inside.::
43::library_043::Holy shroud 	[Armament]::    A cloth used to wrap a saint's body. The shroud used to wrap Shirou's arm is part of the Shroud of Martin.	    Kotomine is believed to have concealed it from the Holy Church.::
44::library_044::Disgracing a saint 	[Miscellaneous]::    Saber when she was held captive by Caster.	    The pure white dress is Miss Caster's personal taste.	    It seems she's really into gothic lolita fashion, but prefers to see cute girls in it since it doesn't suit her. ...Can't she learn some magecraft to restore her youth?	    (Saber's dress isn't a gothic lolita dress.)	    Personally, I think this is the most erotic scene in the main story. Nice, Caster! Keep it coming!::
45::library_045::Holy Church 	[Organization]::  The hidden side of a major, universally present religion which preaches its god's gospel and does not recognize anyone who defies those teachings.	  Heretical entities are publicly treated as if they don't exist, but within the organization are some who passionately work to eliminate all heresy. These heretic hunters specialized in their work and grew into a giant department known as the Holy Church.	  The Church sends its Executors to exterminate demons and erase all heresy. It claims to be the rightful steward of all Mystics, which it sees as beyond humanity's ability to handle.	  It goes without saying that the Church is on poor terms with the Mage's Association, which wants to keep magecraft hidden. The two organizations have come into conflict on numerous occasions. (Currently, they claim to observe a temporary peace agreement.)	  The Holy Church's greatest enemies are the monsters they call "vampires." The Mage's Association sometimes cooperates with the Church to hunt said vampires.	  Kotomine is an Executor assigned to the Assembly of the Eighth Sacrament, a department charged with collecting and managing holy relics.	  The Holy Church's militant power comprises the extraordinarily deadly Executors, the knight companies attached to each congregation, and the monstrous, secretive Burial Agency which answers to Church headquarters.	  It is the largest supernatural organization in the world of <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic>, and the greatest threat to those who have strayed from their humanity.::
46::library_046::Saber [Servant]::    The Heroic Spirit of the sword. It is not possible to qualify for this Servant type unless all abilities, excluding magical energy, are above-standard.	    Saber is one of the official heroines of this story. She is a knight who forms a contract with Shirou Emiya and fights in the Holy Grail War.	    She has an honest and thoroughly diligent personality, and cloaks her girlishness with a knight's pride. Peel that layer away, however, and the young girl shows through.	    She'll pout and not easily forgive you, she'll get too heated and forget about everyone around her in a competition, she'll get really excited over delicious food, and she'll become timid and afraid to fail in front of the person she likes. Hm, what a difficult heroine to please.	    Her true identity is King Arthur.	    She acted as a man, ruled as king, brought peace to her homeland, and perished in a civil war.	    King Arthur in <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> is a melding of history and legend. Before she became king, her name was Altria.	    It must have been exhausting to conceal her gender in court life. The most difficult problem would have been succession, but Merlin's magecraft solved that easily. Saber's line "I know how to please a man" in the main story might have been based on experience.	    Altria stopped aging when she drew the Sword of Selection, so her physical age is the same or perhaps a year younger than Shirou.	    King Arthur was also the Red Dragon protecting Britain. Her father, King Uther Pendragon, conspired with Merlin to create an heir with the factor of a dragon. Thus, Altria was born as a human with the magical energy of a dragon. She doesn't require Magic Circuits; her blood flow and breathing generate magical energy on their own, making her a "magical reactor" on a completely different dimension from mages.	    <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> was her story from the beginning. Its main theme has revolved around the Holy Grail and King Arthur from its earliest stages, and that still hasn't changed.	    A girl knight fighting in the Holy Grail War. I'd like to believe that the dream she has at the end of it all is worthy of the life she led.::
47::library_047::Saber's clothes 	[Miscellaneous]::    The clothes that Rin prepared for Saber. Kirei Kotomine supposedly gifted these to Rin for her birthday.	    Wow, Kotomine's rather...::
48::library_048::Holy Grail 	[Miscellaneous]::    The chalice which held the blood of Christ is a holy relic of the highest order, said to grant the wish of its bearer. It is said to have orignated from numerous older myths of wish-granting cauldrons.	    The Holy Grail that appears in <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> is not the original chalice, but a replica created to function as a wish-granter.	    When Heroic Spirits are destroyed, they return to their original form as pure power and disappear from the time axis. The Einzbern Holy Grail prevents this from occurring and temporarily stores that energy.	    The ritual which opens the path beyond is conducted by the Greater Grail, rather than the Einzberns' Lesser Grail.::
49::library_049::Holy Grail War 	[Miscellaneous]::The conflict to acquire the Holy Grail. It is still called the Holy Grail War even if the Holy Grail is fake, as long as it has the same legendary power to grant wishes.	    The Holy Grail War in Fuyuki uniquely has a system to summon Heroic Spirits and bind them as Servant familiars.	    The Mage's Association holds most of the rights to participate in the war and handles its preparation and agreements... but the Holy Church cannot stand idly by when a relic named the Holy Grail is involved. The Church has decided that it would be the steward of all Holy Grails, regardless of their authenticity, and sends an overseer to Fuyuki, scheming to seize the Holy Grail from the mages should the opportunity arise.	    Basically, the mages from the Association develop the video game, while the Church has the rights to the hardware the game runs on. It's an absurd example that's absurdly fitting at the same time.::
50::library_050::Iskandar, 	King of Conquerors 	[Servant]::Saber's rival in the Fourth Holy Grail War.	    Iskandar has a Noble Phantasm that rivals Gilgamesh, the King of Heroes.	    He was weakened in a battle against Saber, and then lost to Gilgamesh in a subsequent battle.::
51::library_051::Baptismal Rite 	[Magecraft]::    The only miracles permitted to be taught within the Holy Church, Baptismal Rites are simple rituals which sublimate lost souls and send them to the place where they ought to return.	    Each discipline of magecraft engraves the foundation of its magical theory into the world and activates magecraft according to the rules of its respective system.	    Magecraft with lesser faith/foundation is weak, and can even completely cease to function if the mage travels to a different land.	    The magical theory with the most widespread foundation in the world is the teachings and gospel of the Church. Baptismal Rites can only weakly affect the physical, but they have tremendous power against spiritual entities. That the Church's teachings have permeated so widely is a testament to how their miracles, which appeal to the soul, have healed the hearts of many.::
52::library_052::Alignment 	[Miscellaneous]::    The moral alignment of each Servant, viewable on the Status screen, which describes the values that guide their actions and personalities.	    It's fun to compare them, so here are all of them side-by-side.		    Saber: Lawful-Good	    Lancer: Lawful-Balanced	    Archer: Neutral-Balanced	    Rider: Chaotic-Good	    Caster: Neutral-Evil	    Berserker: Chaotic-Madness	    Assassin: Lawful-Evil	    Kojirou: Neutral-Evil	    Gilgamesh: Chaotic-Good	    Dark Saber: Lawful-Evil		    It's not much of a problem when personalities don't match, but there will be more friction between characters if their guiding alignment is the same. Saber and Gil are a good example of this.::
53::library_053::Tiger Dojo 	[Miscellaneous]::    Your game-over buddies who run the Q&A corner that accepts no excuses. They give you hints that seem helpful, but aren't really.	    There's a long series of Tiger Dojos, forty in all. If you watch them all in order, there's actually a flow to them.	    Until two months before master, we kept changing the title transitions, trying to add more animations, trying to give Illya a change of clothes for each episode, and the scenario writer, key animator, and animation director kept pranking each other... If we have that much spare time, shouldn't we focus on increasing the quality of the main story?	    Once we realized that, it settled into its current form.	    Still, all of the animation director's funny animations are intact. On top of that, the Tiger Mini Theater was initially conceived as a part of the full Tiger Dojo.	    Ahh, it's so nice to play a visual novel with a fixed text window. We'll try that next time!::
54::library_054::Executor 	[Miscellaneous]::    Agents of the Holy Church who investigate heresy and eliminate anything which does not exist in Church dogma.	    Executors are different from exorcists in that they exterminate demons rather than drive them away.	    The details are briefly discussed in the latter half of Sakura's route.::
55::library_055::Taxi! [Miscellaneous]::  Helpful taxis are indispensable for traveling to the Einzbern forest. Of course, you have to walk back. Ugh.	  I think the fact that the driver doesn't find it suspicious for a lone high school student to be going to the forest after 3:00AM is way too problematic.	   The car that Kotomine hired wasn't from the Mage's Association or the Holy Church, but Kotomine's own network. During the story's drafting stages, after Shirou accepts Kotomine's help, he says:		   "So, how are you going to help me?"	   "Hmm. With transportation, for starters."		   And then it fades to black.	   There's a mechanical growling sound, and in comes Kotomine on a Harley!	   ...That was in the script, but then I snapped back to my senses and edited it to its current form. Kotomine's trunk is fully stocked with scary weapons, including a submachine gun. Pepesha!::
56::library_056::Blood Fort 	Andromeda 	[Noble Phantasm,	 Magecraft]::    Bloodfort Andromeda, Other-Seal Blood Temple, is a Bounded Field of blood that dissolves the humans caught inside. The dissolved humans turn into a red liquid which the Bounded Field user then collects. Its intended purpose is magical energy collection.	    Rider uses this wide-ranging Bounded Field once in each route.	    The Bounded Field is dome-shaped and appears as a giant eyeball overlooking the school campus. The red sky and dome are, of course, not visible from the outside. As Rin says, only a third-rate mage would allow signs of their work to leak out.	    Because it causes considerable damage to local leylines, Bloodfort Andromeda cannot be used repeatedly on the same land.	    	    ::
57::library_057::Enuma Elish 	[Noble Phantasm]::    Star of Creation that Divided Heaven and Earth. 	    Enuma Elish occurs when Ea, the Sword of Rupture, is used to cut space itself.	    Gaps in compressed, competing wind pressure become quasi-ruptures in space-time and pulverize all who oppose the user.	    This sword once tore the world asunder. It boasts power equal to or greater than Excalibur.	    To be exact, Ea is the Noble Phantasm, while Enuma Elish is the name of Ea's maximum power state.	    As an aside, this drill-shaped sword is modeled after deep-sea boring drills. The word "drill" tends to evoke a sharp and pointed image like a spear, but drills that make giant holes are composed of layers of rotating gears. It's pretty cool to imagine three layers of rotating blades grinding their way through bedrock.::
58::library_058::Chain of the Heavens 	[Armament]::    One of Gilgamesh's preferred Noble Phantasms. Its True Name is Enkidu.	    This chain captured the Bull of Heaven responsible for the seven-year famine in ancient Uruk. Gilgamesh trusts this Noble Phantasm as much as, no, even more than Ea.	    Enkidu has the power to bind gods. The higher the target's Divinity, the stronger this Noble Phantasm becomes. It is one of the few anti-god weapons.	    Thus, this Noble Phantasm is more troublesome to Berserker (Heracles) than Excalibur. 	    On the other hand, it is merely a sturdy chain to Saber, Assassin, and Archer, all of whom lack Divinity.::
59::library_059::Dress of Heaven 	[Armament]::    A magical armament passed down through the Einzbern lineage.	    It contains magecraft which turns it into the control core of the Greater Grail and allows it to materialize souls for a few seconds.	    The dress looks pure white, but is made of gold. It is inlaid with seven rings said to control all of creation and other souls. Each of the seven rings are illuminated as each Servant's soul is stored.	    Only Elementals, dwarves, and homunculi can handle the dress, as it turns any humans who touch it to gold.::
60::library_060::Projection 	[Magecraft]::    Projection magecraft, or Gradation Air, materializes a mirror image of an original item using magical energy. As Rin states in the story, it is very inefficient. 	    If one wishes to create a replica from an original, it's easier to just make it from proper components, and the end product is actually usable.	    Normally, Projection is used to substitute an item for just a few minutes onto the caster's time axis when the original has already been lost.	    Since a Projection is akin to a minutes-long rental that only outwardly resembles the original, it goes without saying how outrageous Shirou and Archer's Projections are. This is why Rin felt a surge of hostility when she peeped on Shirou in the shed.	    Of course, Shirou can only Project items related to weaponry. Even then, he is limited to swords, and can't replicate modern weapons. He can just barely manage shields and armor, but the cost is heavy and they only last for a moment.::
61::library_061::Nagato Tohsaka 	[Person]::    Nagato Tohsaka was a patriarch of the Tohsaka clan, and a co-founder of the Holy Grail War two hundred years ago. He became involved when Zouken Makiri and Justeaze sought his help.	    The Tohsaka ancestors were secret adherents to a foreign religion, but after a strange old man suddenly showed up and invited them, they devoted themselves to the path of magecraft.	    The Tohsaka clan enjoys an enviable position, being acquainted with the Holy Church while also receiving favor from the Mage's Association thanks to being apprentices to a Magician. They administer the land of Fuyuki while maintaining open channels to both organizations.	    Nagato equally pursued magecraft and martial arts. His endeavor to touch the Root through achieving a state of nothingness is what interested him in Einzbern and Makiri's proposal.	    He was something of a klutz, as you might expect from Rin's ancestor. His daughter was apparently more talented in magecraft and made greater strides toward creating the Greater Grail than Nagato did.::
62::library_062::Rin Tohsaka [Person]::    The current head of the Tohsakas, an illustrious family of mages.	    Rin is one of the official heroines of this story. She is one of the Masters and a busy girl who varyingly harasses and helps Shirou.	    She seems aggressive and has a pointed way of speaking, but is a caring, sisterly person at her core.	    The way she makes careless mistakes at the most critical moments is basically a genetic curse at this point.	    Rin is calm and kind, but claims to have a "not cute" personality that makes the rational choice in the end.	    She seems to have a hidden complex about lacking something critical as a girl.	    Perhaps her clothing is a reaction to that, but wouldn't you say that she shows so much leg that a growing young man might not know where to look?	    Hang in there, Shirou.	    Rin's hobbies are jewel appreciation and teasing Shirou. Teasing is in her nature, and she especially likes to torment diligent folks. Keep hanging in there, Shirou.	    Magically, she specializes in the flow and transference of magical energy. Her magical attribute actually isn't well-suited to combat, so she saves up magical energy in her jewels and uses them as convenient, disposable Limited Functions.	    Rin also practices an imitation of karate for self-defense. Her trainer was Kotomine. The way she fought dirty and drove Caster into a corner was very reminiscent of that phony priest.	    She's the character who plays the biggest role in <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> main story.::
63::library_063::Date [Miscellaneous]::    Yay, it's the staple of dating sim games that everybody loves!	    A heroine who lacks date events is no heroine at all. How can you call yourself an official heroine without a date or two!?	    And that's why Saber and Rin have date events.	    You can take them on dates or get taken on dates. It really illustrates the different positions of both heroines, yeah.	   ...Wait.	    Come to think of it, I think there's an official heroine who doesn't have a date event...::
64::library_064::Tiger stripe 	[Miscellaneous]::    The pattern on Fuji-nee's clothes.	    Observant players may notice that those stripes are indeed tiger stripes.	    Early on, we had a weird rule to have Fuji-nee wear normal clothes at school and only switch to tiger stripes at Shirou's house, but at some point she went all-out with the stripes.	    As for what Fuji-nee thinks about tigers, all will become clear in the Tiger Dojo Special.::
65::library_065::Nine Lives 	[Noble Phantasm]::    Nine Lives, or Shooting a Hundred Heads, is Heracles' most trusted Noble Phantasm.	    Heracles used bow and arrow to slay a nine-headed hydra whose heads regenerated and multiplied whenever they were cut off. Afterward, he developed a fighting style that imitated the effects of the bow and arrow, and could even use it with a greatsword.	    If Heracles had been summoned as a Saber, he would have demonstrated his magnificent swordsmanship.	    The technique Shirou used to kill the blackened Berserker was Projected from Berserker, along with his axe-sword.::
66::library_066::But why? 	[Miscellaneous]::    Shirou's catch phrase. It's his conditioned reflex whenever something truly puzzles him.	    Apparently, <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> originally had four routes. But why?::
67::library_067::Noble Color 	[Miscellaneous]::    In magical society, this label is given to those born with unique qualities. It is mainly applied to Mystic Eye bearers. Shiki's eyes in <fzitalic>Tsukihime</fzitalic> qualify as Noble Color.	    Rider's Mystic Eyes of Petrification are classified as Jewel, superior even to the Golden eyes possessed by the greatest vampires.	    And above Jewel is Rainbow, a kaleidoscopic blend of seven prismatic colors. It is said that such eyes mark one as the ruler of the moon.::
68::library_068::Berserker [Servant]::    The mad Heroic Spirit. This Servant type is marked by insanity and being specialized for destruction, regardless of the Heroic Spirit's base abilities.	    The Berserker in this story is already a superior Heroic Spirit, yet his Madness Enhancement has rendered him into an utter monster.	    A normal Master would be unable to control Berserker even with the Command Spells, but Illyasviel, a Holy Grail, possesses special Command Spells which allow her to control him.	    Berserker's true identity is Heracles, the eminent hero of Greek mythology.	    Heracles was stricken by insanity multiple times in myth, so Berserker was likely a comfortable class for him to adapt to.	    Naturally, he easily qualifies for the Saber class, being of superior mind, technique, and strength. If he had been a Saber, he would have demonstrated transcendental swordsmanship.	    Berserker was summoned the earliest, one...no, two months before the Holy Grail War.	    He is unable to act of his own free will because his emotions are sealed. However, no matter how powerful the Command Spells binding him are, he has not lost a certain central part of his mind.	    In Sakura's route, the blackened Heracles was able to stop his axe-sword at the last possible moment thanks to the strength of heart that endured his episodes of madness during the Greek Age of Heroes.	    He's the manliest man in the story of <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic>.::
69::library_069::Rule Breaker 	[Noble Phantasm]::Rule Breaker, All Spells Must Be Broken, is a dagger which nullifies all magecraft.	    It is the ultimate anti-magecraft Noble Phantasm which renders magically Strengthened matter, contractually bound relationships, and living beings created from magical energy all back to the state before they were created.	    Rule Breaker does have limits, however; it cannot reset a Noble Phantasm, no matter how low of a rank it is.	    It is a fitting Noble Phantasm for Caster which she used to great effect to conquer Saber. Understated, yet incredible.::
70::library_070::Rogue Servant 	[Miscellaneous]::    A potential heroine who was cut during the story draft stage.	    She was planned to be an abandoned puppy sort of heroine who went out of control after killing her Master.	    A Shielder type Servant, she would have been Saber's rival...but at some point she disappeared.	    Like Gilgamesh, we thought about having her stick around after the last war, but decided that too many characters would confuse the player, so we scrapped her.	    Back then, the plot was meandering. It was a scary, chaotic time when even Rider and Caster were potential heroines.	    Fuji-nee? Fuji-nee's never had a main route, even in the drafts.::
71::library_071::Bazett Fraga 	McRemitz [Person]::    Lancer's original Master. It is unknown whether she's alive or dead.	    Bazett is a visiting mage dispatched from the Mage's Association. She used runestone earrings as a catalyst to summon Lancer.	    She's a pretty woman who dresses in men's suits, and her mage skills are A+.	    Bazett is a bold, militant mage who goes out to capture Seal Designated mages. She occupies a similar position to the Church's Executors and possesses excellent magical and fighting skills.	    She would have posed a threat to Rin if she'd joined the war, but retired due to Kotomine's trickery before she could. On that note, Bazett and Kotomine are old acquaintances, being comrades-in-arms from the years when Kotomine was still a Church Executor. They fought with and against each other at various times.	    When she was sent by the Association, Kotomine asked to meet with her, saying he needed her counsel. He had never asked her for help before, so Bazett hid her happiness and trusted Kotomine, which is how she got tricked.	    Before Bazett could even bring out Lancer, Kotomine cut her down from behind, severed her left arm, and stole her Command Spells. Then, he cast two Command Spells on Lancer:	    The first forced him to agree to change Masters. The second ordered him to focus on gathering intelligence.	    As for the final Command Spells, it's as it played out in the main story.::
72::library_072::Parameters 	[Miscellaneous]::    The scores that quantify each Servant's abilities, for no particular reason.	    You're probably wondering, "A is clearly the strongest, but what about B+ or A+?"	    Here's a brief explanation.	    If we consider a normal value to be 1, then E is 10. Each rank goes up by 10, with rank A being 50.	    As for B+ and A+, the plus represents a special ability that can briefly double that score.	    In other words, a B+ ability can't normally beat A, but 40 can momentarily double to 80, surpassing the 50 of rank A.	    Think of it this way: Heroic Spirits with plusses (+) are rare, only the overpowered ones have double plus (++), and who let the guy with a triple plus (+++) in here!?	    There's also the EX rank, which denotes exceptional abilities that can't be quantified by the E thru A scores.	    Gilgamesh's base parameters are relatively weak, but his Noble Phantasm being EX rank makes him one of the greatest Heroic Spirits.::
73::library_073::Anti-Hero 	[Miscellaneous]::    Entities that are despised by the people, whose evil acts result in many people being saved, and so prove their goodness through evil.	    Saviors who are the subject of curses, yet are venerated, are anti-heroes.	    That said, pure anti-heroes do not exist. Some are thoroughly evil, but end up committing good acts. Assassin and Archer qualify as such.	    Rider and Caster aren't proper Heroic Spirits, but neither are they complete anti-heroes.::
74::library_074::Kane Himuro [Person]::    One of the friendly trio in Class 2-A. She tends to be the straight man of the group.	    Kane is an ace of the track and field club with a strong high jump. You'd think she doesn't like her old-fashioned name, but she's rather fond of it.	    She'd actually rather draw, but Makidera dragged her into the track and field club.::
75::library_075::Invisible Air 	[Noble Phantasm,	 Magecraft]::    Invisible Air, or Barrier of the Wind King, is an invisible sword coated in numerous layers of wind which change the light refraction to conceal the blade.	    Technically, this is magecraft, not a Noble Phantasm. Its effect is simple but highly effective in close combat, preventing Saber's opponent from gauging the reach of her weapon.	    It increases accuracy and defense, but if the opponent has resistance to visual obstruction penalties, then Invisible Air is just a sword covered in wind.	    It has no effect against enemies with the skill Mind's Eye (False) or resistance to illusions.	    While it is one of Saber's primary weapons, its true intent is only to be a sheath to hide her holy sword, as Kojirou surmises.::
76::library_076::Fujimura Group 	[Organization]::    Fuji-nee's family. Illya ends up living with them in the epilogue of Saber's route.	    Fuji-nee's grandpa Raiga is the boss. Fuji-nee's father is a big, reliable, stoic man who was adopted into the family.	    Is this family's hands-off approach how they produced such a troublemaker?	    Shirou often plays along with Grandpa Raiga's hobbies for pocket money.::
77::library_077::Taiga Fujimura 	[Person]::    A.K.A. Fuji-nee, the mysterious woman who sneaks into the Emiya house.	    Her true identity is an English teacher. Her primary goal is hanging out at Shirou's house.	    She doesn't like her given name Taiga, and she gets mad if you call her Tiger. Also, she'll cry.	    Fuji-nee's personality is all sunshine, but her indulgent lifestyle makes one worry for her future.	    In the True Ending of Sakura's route, Fuji-nee stays the same while everyone else around her has grown up. You'd think she hasn't aged since her twenties.	    During her student years, she was apparently a renowned fencer and the idol of the kendo club.	    She's been visiting the Emiya house frequently ever since Kiritsugu Emiya bought the house on the hill.	    It seems that she fell for Kiritsugu at first sight and would butt heads with Shirou when she came to visit. In time, they reconciled and grew into their current relationship.	    Fuji-nee is a beloved character among our entire staff. She was a more upstanding big sister during the story's drafting stage... That's weird. How did she turn into someone like this..?	    She's had short hair since she was a student.::
78::library_078::Noble Phantasm 	[Armament]::    The treasured relics and armaments built upon human imagination and wielded by Heroic Spirits.	    Noble Phantasms are primarily swords, spears, and bows, but there are also Heroic Spirits whose Noble Phantasms are supplemental armaments such as shields, rings, and crowns.	    Each is a Mystic unto itself.  A Noble Phantasm demonstrates its full powers when it is fed magical energy and its True Name is invoked.::
79::library_079::Jewel Magecraft 	[Magecraft]::    The magecraft that Rin specializes in. Jewel Magecraft uses jewels that easily accept the user's thoughts and readily store magical energy.	    Minerals that have slept in the earth for a long time are easiest for Nature Spirits to inhabit, and elementally aspected jewels can inherently serve as Magic Crests. For example, magical energy channeled through a jewel containing a Nature Spirit of fire is more combustible.	    Rin transfers her power into jewels whenever she has a spare moment. The jewels serve as powerful bullets, but Jewel Magecraft makes heavy use of expendable components.	    It's said that Tohsaka mages, who turn precious gems to ash with a single use, are always plagued by financial trouble.::
80::library_080::Scrapped routes 	[Miscellaneous]::    As the name suggests, these are the routes that didn't make it into the final cut of the game.	    Initially, <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> was conceived with four routes each for four heroines. The player could choose to play as either Shirou or Rin in the first half. The two would meet at the midpoint, and the game would then branch into four routes for the latter half of the war... That's the kind of uncertain structure the plot had.	    As you know, the Illya route was cut from the game.	    Also, there was a Rider route where you fought against Rin and Saber, and a Caster route where you could turn Caster into a little girl and make her your partner.	    The Caster route was completely wiped out, but the part where you work together with Rider still made it into the final story in a limited form.	    If there had been an Illya route, it would have branched off from the 9th day of Sakura's route, where you could choose to be on Illya's side, rather than becoming a hero or staying on Sakura's side.	    Unfortunately, that possibility ceased to exist in the story.::
81::library_081::Mystic Eyes 	[Magecraft]::    Mystic Eyes mainly allow mages to cast Single Action spells. 	    Originally, Mystic Eyes resulted from transforming the eyes from organs which receive information from the environment into organs which affect the environment.	    Bluntly put, they unilaterally enact magecraft on anything in the bearer's sight, and the effect is greatly amplified if a target makes eye contact with the Mystic Eyes.	    In other words, Mystic Eyes are a fearsome magical trait which ensnares anyone they look upon, and should never be looked back at.	    Due to their concealability and power, Mystic Eyes are considered to be the mark of a first-rate mage.	    However, artificially induced Mystic Eyes are limited to Charm and Mesmerize effects.	    Powerful Mystic Eye bearers are born with their powers. They are psychic powers which cannot be recreated with magecraft, such as Rider's Mystic Eyes of Petrification, or Mystic Eyes that see the death of all things.::
82::library_082::Kaede Makidera 	[Person]::    One of the merry trio in Class 2-A. Kaede is a sprinter in the track and field club who wants to be known as the Black Panther of Homurahara. She also goes by Maki-G.	    The honor student Rin Tohsaka is her friend and someone she'd like to get one over on. She views Ayako Mitsuzuri, one of Rin's few friends, as a rival.	    Kaede enjoys collecting wind chimes and she loves glass blowing. On weekends, she can be seen browsing antique shops with Rin thanks to their shared interest.::
83::library_083::Demonic Beast 	[Miscellaneous]::    An umbrella name for beasts in the world of <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> which don't fit into natural ecology. They are broadly classified into the ranks of Demonic, Phantasmal, and Divine.	    Many Demonic Beasts are chimeras and live in undeveloped lands, while Phantasmal Beasts have shifted to the hidden side of the world due to their nature.	    Rider's winged horse is a Demonic Beast, but it has reached the realm of the Phantasmal after living for such a long time. Most mages cannot handle Phantasmal Beasts.	    Draconic creatures are considered the greatest of their kind, regardless of rank. Because there are dragonkin of all three types, they have had many interactions with humans.::
84::library_084::Magecraft 	[Magecraft]::    A general term for manmade Mystics and miracles.	    While magecraft differs by discipline, they all have the basic structure of converting magical energy within the caster's body or the atmosphere.	    Each discipline enacts magecraft by issuing a command to a foundation (system) and executing a premade function (program).	    The electrical current required to issue said command is magical energy.	    One might imagine mages as all-powerful, but they fundamentally cause Mystics using equivalent exchange.	    Rin is supremely talented, but her magical affinity that allows her to use magecraft on anything means that she has to pay a heavy price, and it seems that she's destined to face financial difficulty for the rest of her life.	    Also, there is no physical cost to interfere with someone else's mind or alter their thoughts, but the caster's mind will also be pulled along in the direction that they choose.	    As the saying goes, when you want to curse someone, dig two graves.	    The Mage's Association has no department specializing in curses, and greatly lags behind Middle Eastern magecraft in this regard.::
85::library_085::Magic Circuit 	[Magecraft]::    Pseudo-nerves in a mage's body that function as channels to convert life energy to magical energy, and serve as the connection to foundational magecraft formulae.	    One's number of circuits is determined at birth. A mage lineage will do everything it can to increase a successor's circuits by even one.	    Once a mage opens their Magic Circuits for the first time, they can turn them on and off at will. The "switch" varies according to the caster's imagination. Shirou pictures a firearm trigger, while Rin imagines a knife stabbing her in the heart.	    This is related to how the circuits were first opened. Some have their circuits opened through sexual arousal, while others can only open them with self-harm.	    It bears mentioning that Shirou has a surprising number of circuits: 27.	    Rin has 40 main circuits, and each circuit has 30 sub-circuits.::
86::library_086::Mage's Association 	[Organization]::    An organization for collective self-defense (in name only, of course), created for the study of magecraft and unbound by nationality or genre.	    The Association's mission is the stewardship, concealment, and development of magecraft.	    It possesses martial might to defend itself from threats (the Church, other magical organizations, monstrosities that punish humans who break taboos), research facilities to further (some would say regress) the development of magecraft, and laws to prevent crimes from being committed with magecraft.	    The headquarters, located in London, is frequently referred to as the Clock Tower.	    It is said that the Association was divided into three major branches in its infancy. The Titan's Pit is located in Egypt. The Wandering Sea is a collection of organizations with roots in Northern Europe, and was the original Association until the Clock Tower became the primary branch, after which the Wandering Sea ceased contact with the others.	    The magecraft foundations of the Middle East and continental Europe are incompatible, and both sides claim to observe a policy of mutual non-aggression.::
87::library_087::Magic Crest 	[Magecraft]::The legacy of a mage lineage.	    Mages spend their lifetimes cultivating and fixating (stabilizing) Mystics into their Crest, and pass it down to their offspring.	    It is no exaggeration to say that a bloodline's entire history is engraved in its Crest. The mage who inherits the Magic Crest shoulders their clan's regrets and has no choice but to pass it down to the next heir.	    In a way, it could be described as a curse built generation upon generation.::
88::library_088::Sakura Matou 	[Person]::    One of the official heroines of this story.	    Sakura is a headline-worthy heroine with vibrant, long hair, a soothing smile, and secretly the best proportions of the three. But she's still an unlucky, unremarkable girl.	    She's the heroine who best symbolizes a normal life, but... Through some mistake, she meets the most tragic fate in every route.	    It's only natural, as her initial concept was based on Fujino Asagami. There was no way she would not be witness to bloodshed.	    Sakura is one year younger than Shirou, and their first meeting is rather complicated. She saw Shirou doing the high jump one April, four years ago, met him when he came over to the Matou house to hang out with her brother, did her very best to say hello to him when he came over, and started helping out at his house a year and a half before this story begins. Afterward, she gradually got used to the Emiya household, was influenced by Fuji-nee, and turned into the bright and spirited Sakura Matou we know.	    She has a mild personality, and she's very patient. Troublingly, she essentially doesn't resent other people, but tends to blame herself for everything.	    She doesn't hold a grudge against Shinji or big man Zouken, yet reacts only to Rin because Rin is the person that's most like her. It's like she can only be honest with someone similar to herself, if not herself. Yeah.	    As you all know, Sakura is the kind of girl who seems passive but really goes for something when she wants it, and is the one girl in the story who is the best at seduction. She's always wearing that "I love Senpai" aura, but it's hard to tell if Shirou's realized how she feels.	    She's a naughty woman with strong maternal instincts who will spoil you as much as you want. Sweet honey turns men useless, you know. Not that Hariti cares!	    Is she the most popular heroine among the staff?	    She actually has some pretty unhinged supporters who call her "the heroine who gets driven into the corner," "the heroine who's messed up somehow," "I love my big brother (heart)," etc.::
89::library_089::Shinji Matou [Person]::  Shirou's friend and Sakura Matou's big brother. Shinji is Rider's Master and clashes with the protagonist several times.	  He has a bad habit of being self-centered and looking down on others, but there's a certain thread to his actions that makes him twisted and troubled, but not evil.	  He's a guy who places importance on rules (that he doesn't follow much himself), dislikes inequality (unless he's the source of it), and is nice to girls (but not girls that belong to him)... I see, he really is one of the top two nicest guys at school.	  Shinji's personality was warped by the disparity between his idealized world and the world he exists in, but he wasn't this bad before he met Shirou.	  They first met four years ago. Shirou was doing chores for free, of course. Shinji (sincerely) mocked him from behind, saying "you must be stupid," but stayed with him until he was finished. He seemed to enjoy himself, laughing, "you're an idiot, but you do good work."	  Shirou must have seen something in the foul-mouthed but candid Shinji. From then on, they became close friends who would often spend time together.	  Shinji would continue to make fun of Shirou. From the shadows, however, he would socially murder anyone who took advantage of Shirou and often invited him over to the Matou house, acting more or less like a best friend.	  Still, as players are well aware, he's a self-proclaimed genius with a difficult personality, so although he and Shirou have been friends for a number of years, he suddenly turns enemy for unclear reasons.	  He's the archetype of a person who's helpful to have on your side, but becomes a very troublesome enemy.	  We planned to create a story branch when Shinji offers to team up with you in Saber's route, but had to cut it when we ran out of time.	  Oh, if that route (let's call it the Shinji route) had existed, you might have seen more of Shinji's redeeming qualities, but we seriously had our hands full so please forgive us.::
90::library_090::Zouken Matou 	[Person]::    Bizarre Bug Gramps. Next.	    The scenario writer loves him. My typing speed palpably increases whenever he shows up.	    Always gotta have a creepy old guy in fantasy fiction. Heh heh.::
91::library_091::Magic [Miracle]::    Mystics of a different sort than magecraft, and the final destination of mages.	    Magic is that which makes something that is impossible to achieve in the current era possible. Outcomes that can be produced with enough time and resources are not considered Magic.	    When civilization was young, the majority of mages were Magicians, but now, only five remain, and of them, only four are living. The user of the First Magic is long deceased.	    Two of the remaining four Magicians are shrouded in mystery, while the other two are known to frequently appear and cause a commotion before leaving. They really are troublemakers.::
92::library_092::Unused 	[Miscellaneous]::    Assets that we created but didn't end up using. They mostly consist of standing character portraits.	    We didn't necessarily need to, but <fzitalic>Fate</fzitalic> was conceived with the idea to create near, mid, and far versions of all standing portraits.	    When the game was finished, the total number of standing portraits alone was 3600. Of course, we didn't manage to use them all, and it would have resulted in 	4 CDs' worth of content, so we tearfully removed the unused art.	    Let's optimize this better next time, everyone. We'll shoot for a casual game that takes two hours per playthrough.::
93::library_093::Ayako Mitsuzuri 	[Person]::A female student in Class 2-A. Ayako is the captain of the kyudo club and a friend who is a bad influence on Rin and Shirou.	  She and Rin are mutually bad influences on each other, while she treats Shirou as a rival. She hasn't noticed that the three of them share a rather odd relationship.	  Ayako is even more sisterly than Rin, and she's seen as one of the three worst people to pick a fight with at Homurahara High School. It's easy to see her as headstrong and masculine, but she's rather feminine in her private life.	  One might think Ayako prefers to hide the gap between perception and reality, but she doesn't particularly care. Her bedroom is adorned with girly things, and she doesn't hesitate to invite Rin over.	  It isn't that Ayako isn't interested in romance, but she just prefers older guys. First Rin, now you... does everyone have a father complex?	  We put more effort into Ayako's design to shore up the supporting cast, and it might not surprise you that her design was initially meant for Rider.	  When Fate was in pre-production, the scenario writer, who was obsessed with a film called Vi--cq, personally asked to make Rider look more like that man in the black cowl. This suggestion was proposed as Mitsuzuri's design, but it was too close to Medusa's image, so it was rejected. We still couldn't bear to send her to the monster graveyard, so I'm glad Ayako Mitsuzuri was ultimately resurrected in some form. Thank goodness.	  You're not allowed to say that she looks like Shiki Ryougi.	  You might be interested to know that Micchan is just as peppy as ever after Rin's route. Rider was the Servant who attacked her, and it's believed she cornered Ayako in an alley and slurped up her blood. Here's hoping she doesn't develop a weird kink...::
94::library_094::Unlimited 	Blade Works 	[Noble Phantasm,	 Magecraft]::   Infinite Sword Creation.	    Unlimited Blade Works is treated as a Noble Phantasm, but to be exact, it is a form of magecraft called a Reality Marble.	    This Reality Marble contains the materials needed to make all swords. Any sword its user has seen can be easily replicated. However, replicated weapons are degraded by one rank. Defensive equipment can be replicated as well, but they require two to three times the magical energy of a usual Projection. Once a piece of equipment has been replicated, it is registered in the Reality Marble and can be created with Projection magecraft without activating the Reality Marble.	    Against most opponents, this Noble Phantasm is merely a somewhat troublesome ability, but it is the perfect countermeasure to the King of Heroes.::
95::library_095::Zabaniya 	[Noble Phantasm,	 Magecraft]::  Delusional Heartbeat.	  This Noble Phantasm is the cursed arm of the evil spirit Shaytan. It is specialized at cursing humans to death.	  Using an ether clump, it creates a duplicate mirror entity of the target. When the fake is crushed, it resonates with the target, making it possible to inflict a lethal curse on the target without laying a finger on them.	  It is a roundabout method of murder, but well-suited to assassination. Even if the target is protected by armor with a defensive value of 1000, Zabaniya can crush the copy of the target's heart to deal direct damage within the armor.	  It is a Noble Phantasm that uses a stage magician's tricks.::
96::library_096::Excalibur 	[Noble Phantasm]::    Excalibur, the Sword of Promised Victory, is a sword of light. It is a god-forged weapon created by the planet, rather than by human hands. This Noble Phantasm stands at the apex of all holy swords.	    It is the ultimate fantasy (Lost Phantasm) crystalized and tempered within the planet from the gathered wishes for "how the world ought to be" from all people on the Earth's surface.	    Excalibur was in the custody of Elementals who serve as the planet's sense of touch, but it passed into the hands of a human king for a time.	    Its excessive fame as the symbol of King Arthur forces Saber to fight while concealing her sword's true nature.	    While this Noble Phantasm can be considered a synonym for Saber herself, she only uses it a few times. It was used thrice in Saber's route, once in Rin's route, and twice in Sakura's route.	    Because it is so powerful, it cannot be recklessly used on the planet's surface.	    Excalibur's black-and-white clash with Rider's Bellerophon can be described as the most splendid flower in all of Fate.::
97::library_097::Justeaze Lizrich von 	Einzbern [Person]::The matriarch of the Einzbern two hundred years ago, who became the cornerstone of the Greater Grail.	    Like Illya, Justeaze did not possess a proper human body. She was a Magic Circuit born to serve as the reactor core of the Greater Grail.	    Illya is the latest model of Einzbern homunculus, conceived between a mother based on the Justeaze pattern and a foreign mage.	     Justeaze is still contained in the core of the Greater Grail to this day. The circuit that tightly lines the crater's surface is made from her expanded and propagated Magic Circuits. At nearly a kilometer in diameter, the Greater Grail's Magic Circuits are a microcosm composed of a single human body.::
98::library_098::Rider [Servant]::    The cavalier Heroic Spirit. This Servant type tends to possess high mobility and powerful Noble Phantasms.	    The Rider in this story rides a Pegasus, making full use of its charging power in combat.	    Rider herself is a unique Heroic Spirit who possesses perhaps the greatest number of innate skills and Noble Phantasms among the Servants.	    While Rider is a woman of few words, she is hardly indifferent to her surroundings. In fact, she hides her tendency to overthink things behind a poker face. Her personality resembles Sakura's in some ways, but she has the disposition of a noblewoman, while Sakura is a commoner. Her mannerisms and speech even give off an upper-class sternness.	    Rider has a complex about her height, is embarrassed to show her Mystic Eyes, and might be a generally modest person.	    Before release, some people guessed that she might be Assassin based on her appearance and weapons, but she turned out to be Rider. Heh.	    We wanted to include a scene in Sakura's route where she fights alongside Saber, with whom she does not get along well, while trading grievances. Sadly, we had to shelve that idea.	    By the way, Rider is responsible for the lewd dream on day 5 of Sakura's route. She isn't a Dead Apostle, but she is vampiric. For her, the most efficient and delicious way to obtain magical energy is drinking blood.::
99::library_099::Lancer [Servant]::  The spear-wielding Heroic Spirit. This Servant type is a dependable, no-frills class that prioritizes the highest agility, as well as excellent close combat skills.	  Lancer's vulgar, brutish demeanor is a stark contrast to his righteous and amiable nature. He's a concrete example of the young man who is strong in body but gentle in spirit.	  His true identity is the great Celtic hero CĂş Chulainn. If this Holy Grail War took place outside of Japan, his renown would have been as brilliant as that of Heracles or King Arthur.	  As described in this story, CĂş Chulainn is a Heroic Spirit who excels at survival. He can return alive from any deadly battlefield, but it can only be said that he has poor luck this time.	  In legend, he is said to be a man "roused by the cries of battle into a demonic dance."	  CĂş Chulainn also qualifies as a Berserker, but in the end, Lancer suits him the best. His desire is to fight for his life and this was his price for answering the summons, but his wish was never granted.	  This tragically unlucky Servant embodies the irony of unfulfilled wishes.::
100::library_100::Dragon Tooth 	Warrior [Magecraft]::    Familiars created from dragon teeth. When the earth is sown with the teeth, the dragon's magical energy and the wisdom of the earth combine to produce disposable infantry.	    We created three different types of standing portraits, and they're all quite lovely.	    Tabletop RPG players will find them nostalgic. They're incredibly strong minions that can give level 5 adventurers a run for their money.::
101::library_101::Issei Ryudou [Person]::  A male student in Class 2-C, and the student council president. He met and befriended Shirou two years ago.	  Issei has a stiff and joyless personality, but that doesn't mean he can't be accommodating.	  He is the youngest son of Ryudou Temple and apparently wants to be a monk when he grows up. According to him, his spiritual senses are weak.	  He takes a two-hour commute to school every day like it's nothing. Monks who train in the mountains are strong walkers.	  Issei has known Rin for quite a while, and it's believed that his two-year secret war with her is the cause of his misogyny. RIP. But he does acknowledge Rin's human qualities, and that bothers him.	  Issei reveres Souichirou Kuzuki as his mentor and spars with him on the weekends. He probably would have joined the karate club if he hadn't become the student council president.	  His favorite food is Shirou's homemade lunches.::
102::library_102::Ryudou Temple 	[Miscellaneous]::  The mountain temple on the outskirts of Miyama.	  As its name suggests, Ryudou Temple is a nexus for leylines. One can consider it the spiritual heart of Fuyuki.	  A large cavern is beneath the temple. The pond behind the temple is ostensibly the summoning site of the Holy Grail.	  Following the cave-in in Sakura's route, it took several years after the epilogue to rebuild the temple.	  ...The primary reason for the cave's collapse wasn't AĹ‹ra Mainiiu's disappearance, but rather Rin's shooting spree.	  Impressive, Issei. For identifying Rin as a foe of the Buddha, you really ought to inherit the temple.::
103::library_103::Rin's pendant 	[Miscellaneous]::    Powerful jewel magecraft passed down to Rin from her father.	    It once contained enough magical energy to revive a person from the brink of death.	    Rin used it all to save Shirou in the prologue. She might have seemed hesitant, but her mental seek time between seeing his body and acting was actually less than one second. She's a decisive woman.	    Once Shirou woke up, he pocketed the pendant in a daze and went home.	     See the main story to find out how the pendant made its way back into Rin's hands.	    I was a little worried that demo players might pick up on that right away.::
104::library_104::Luviagelita Edelfelt 	[Person]::    The heiress to the illustrious Edelfelt lineage of mages. She is a current candidate for the seat of a Lord of the Clock Tower.	    Luvia was a flawless woman blessed with graceful bearing, refined speech, and swanlike beauty...	    ...until Rin Tohsaka showed up, that is.	    As the saying goes, "Birds of a feather flock together," but it's hard to say who flocked to who first in this situation. One thing's for sure: these two are utterly similar to each other.	    Having unexpectedly met a rival in Rin, Luvia increasingly abandons her ladylike pretense in favor of violent conflict every time they meet.	    After a year, the Mineralogy department has agreed on an unspoken consensus to "never attend a class where Tohsaka and Edelfelt are competing."	    Like Rin, Luvia specializes in Jewel Magecraft and is a master of the Gandr Shot, befitting her Finnish sensibilities. (She is not to be considered a Finnish role model.)	    Elegant, a sore loser, and meticulous to a fault, it would be stranger if this perfect superwoman didn't butt heads with Rin.	    Despite treating her rival like the sky isn't big enough for two suns, Luvia's a delightful young lady who enjoys teasing Rin. She's cranky at having her perfect veneer stripped off after some ten-odd years of flawless conduct, but she finds her time with Rin to be fulfilling, so all's well that ends well.	    She bought an entire manor to live in, haughtily complaining that the student dorms were too cramped.::
105::library_105::Rho Aias 	[Noble Phantasm]::    Rho Aias, the Seven Rings Cradling the Burning Heavens, is the shield used by Aias in the Trojan War, one of the greatest wars in Greek mythology.	    Aias bore a bronze shield reinforced by seven layers of ox-hide, and used it to block a spear thrown by the Trojan hero Hektor, who was said to be able to pierce any defense. (The spear pierced six layers of hide and was stopped by the seventh.)	    Afterward, its fame as a Conceptual Weapon with absolute defensive power against thrown weapons spread, and it was sublimated as a Noble Phantasm.	    Rho Aias is the only defensive armament that Archer is proficient with.	    At the end of Rin's route, the Rho Aias that protected Shirou during his incantation wasn't deployed by Shirou, but by Archer observing the battle from afar.::
106::library_106::Wild Wild England 	[Miscellaneous]::    The small episode that unfolds on the night of the 10th day of Rin's route, if you choose Saber.	    This lighthearted anecdote gives us a glimpse into the length and depth of Saber's sinful relationship with food.	    Let us avoid speculating whether their cooking was too wild, or whether it was a problem of her personal tastes.::IÚ